Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into small pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Chop into 1cm sized chunks. Trim the @green beans{80%g} and chop into thirds. Trim the @courgette{1}, quarter lengthways and cut into 1cm chunks.

Pour the cold @water{300%ml} for the rice into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}. Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp}, cover with the lid and bring to the boil on medium-high heat. Once boiling, turn the heat down to its lowest setting. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #large frying pan{} over medium heat and add the onion. Cook, stirring occasionally, until softened and starting to turn golden, ~{6-7%minutes}. Add the pepper to the pan with the onions, stir and cook for ~{1%minute}. Stir in the @tandoori masala spice{1%tsp} and cook for ~{30%seconds}. Now add the @ginger puree{1/2%tsp}, garlic and @tomato puree{30%g}, stir and cook for another ~{30%seconds}.

Pour in the @water{150%ml} for the curry, the @creme fraiche{75%g}, @coconut milk{200%ml} and @vegetable stock paste{10%g}. Bring to the boil, stirring to combine, then reduce the heat to medium. Stir in the green beans and courgette, cover the pan with a lid (or some #tin foil{}) and simmer until the veg are almost tender, ~{8-9%minutes}. Remove the lid and allow to simmer until the mixture has thickened and the veggies are cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes}, stirring occasionally.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @coriander{1%bunch} (stalks and all). When the curry is cooked, season to taste with salt and pepper if needed, add the @?chilli flakes{1%tsp} (if you want a bit of spice) and stir in half the coriander.

> Add a splash of water if it's looking a bit thick.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}. Serve the rice in bowls topped with plenty of veggie tikka and the remaining coriander. Enjoy!